<h1>Latest news 04-11-2023</h1>


 <h2>NuTyX 23.11.0 available with cards 2.7.1</h2>
  <p>
   Spiky and me are happy to announce the new version of NuTyX 23.11.0 and cards 2.7.1 .

 <h2>Fixed bugs</h2>
  <p>
   <table width="60%" cellspacing="0">
    <tr>
     <td>
      cards list -p doesn't display any version-release info.
     </td>
     <td>
      Fixed
     </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td>
      cards info -p <package_name> displays no info.
     </td>
     <td>
      Fixed
     </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td>
      install-nutyx -ec mounts the folders each time the command is run.
      You end up with the same setup several times.
     </td>
     <td>
      Fixed
     </td>
    </tr>
  </table>

 <h2>Updated packages</h2>
 <p>
   SysV in 3.06 and systemd in 253.0 .
  <p>
   The xorg-server graphics server version 21.1.9,
   the Mesa 3D library in 23.2.1, Gtk4 4.12.0
   and Qt 6.6.0.
  <p>
   <ul>
    <li>
     The nvidia driver is update to version  535.113.01 .
    <li>
     The legacy driver 470.xx series in version 470.199.02 .
    <li>
     The legacy driver 390.xx series in version 390.157.12 .
   </ul>
  <p>
   The python interpreter is updated to version 3.11.5.
  <p>
   The XFCE desktop environment is updated to version 4.18.3.
  <p>
   The MATE desktop environment is a 1.26.2 version .
  <p>
   The GNOME desktop environment is also updated to version 45.0
   <p>
   The KDE desktop environment is available in Plasma 5.27.9, Framework 5.111.0
   and applications in 23.08.2.
  <p>
   Available browsers are: Firefox 119.0, Epiphany 45.0, etc
  <p>
   Many desktop applications have been updated as well like Telegram-desktop 4.10.3,
   Thunderbird 115.4.1, Scribus 1.5.8, Libreoffice 7.5.4.2, Gimp 2.10.34, etc.
  <p>
   Core NuTyX ships with Long Term Support (LTS) kernels:
   4.14.328, 4.19.297, 5.4.259, 5.10.199, 5.15.137, 6.1.60
   and the latest stable version 6.5.9 .
  <p>
   The kernel change logs are available here:
  <p>
  <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v4.x/ChangeLog-4.14.328">kernel 4.14.328 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v4.x/ChangeLog-4.19.297">kernel 4.19.297 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v5.x/ChangeLog-5.4.259">kernel 5.4.259 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v5.x/ChangeLog-5.10.199">kernel 5.10.199 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v5.x/ChangeLog-5.15.137">kernel 5.15.137 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v6.x/ChangeLog-6.1.60">kernel 6.1.60 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v6.x/ChangeLog-6.5.9">kernel 6.5.9 changelog</a>
  <p>
   A BASE ISO (proposed in command line interface edition only without graphical interface).
  <p>
   13 desktops are now available in:
   XORG,
   OPENBOX,
   LXDE,
   XFCE4,
   JWM,
   CDE,
   LXQT,
   ENLIGHTENMENT,
   MATE,
   CINNAMON,
   BUDGIE,
   GNOME,
   KDE5.
  <p>
   They are available on the <a href="downloads">download page.</a>

 <h2>Upgrade process</h2>
  <p>
   A simple:
 </p><pre class="command_user"><kbd>sudo cards upgrade</kbd></pre>
   will make it.

 <h2>Thanks</h2>
  <p>
   With Thanks to the BLFS Team which helped out with a few problems we encountered.
  <p>
   Thanks to Spiky for his patience and his generosity in upgrading all thoses many packages.
  <p>
   Thanks to all you guys that have giving us positive or negative feedbacks about the distribution.

